<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Litigation and Patent Reexaminations
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The Company owns numerous patents and continues to enlarge and strengthen its patent portfolios, which cover different aspects of the Company&#x2019;s technology innovations with various claim scopes. The Company plans to generate revenue by selling or licensing its technology, and intends to vigorously enforce its patent rights against infringers of such rights. The Company dedicates substantial resources in protecting its intellectual property, including its efforts to defend its patents against challenges made by way of reexamination proceedings at the USPTO. These activities are likely to continue for the foreseeable future, without any guarantee that any ongoing or future patent protection and litigation activities will be successful. The Company is also subject to litigation claims that it has infringed on the intellectual property of others, against which the Company intends to defend vigorously.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:27PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Litigation, whether or not eventually decided in the Company&#x2019;s favor or settled, is costly and time-consuming and could divert management&#x2019;s attention and resources. Because of the nature and inherent uncertainties of litigation, should the outcome of any of such actions be unfavorable, the Company&#x2019;s business, financial condition, results of operations or cash flows could be materially and adversely affected. Additionally, the outcome of pending litigation, and the related patent reexaminations, as well as any delay in their resolution, could affect the Company&#x2019;s ability to license its intellectual property in the future or to protect against competition in the current and expected markets for its products.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Google Litigation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In May&nbsp;2008, the Company initiated discussions with Google,&nbsp;Inc. (&#x201C;Google&#x201D;) based on information and belief that Google had infringed on a U.S. patent owned by the Company, U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;7,289,386 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;386 patent&#x201D;), which relates generally to technologies to implement rank multiplication in memory modules. Preemptively, Google filed a declaratory judgment lawsuit against the Company in the U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California (the &#x201C;Northern District Court&#x201D;), seeking a declaration that Google did not infringe the &#x2018;386 patent and that the &#x2018;386 patent
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	24
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage80"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	was invalid. The Company filed a counterclaim for infringement of the &#x2018;386 patent by Google. Claim construction proceedings were held in November&nbsp;2009, and the Company prevailed on every disputed claim construction issue. In June&nbsp;2010, the Company filed motions for summary judgment of patent infringement and dismissal of Google&#x2019;s affirmative defenses. In May&nbsp;2010, Google requested and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;386 patent by the USPTO. The reexamination proceedings are described below. The Northern District Court granted Google&#x2019;s request to stay the litigation pending result of the reexamination, and therefore has not ruled on the Company&#x2019;s motions for summary judgment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In December&nbsp;2009, the Company filed a patent infringement lawsuit against Google in the Northern District Court, seeking damages and injunctive relief based on Google&#x2019;s infringement of U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;7,619,912 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;912 patent&#x201D;), which is related to the &#x2018;386 patent and relates generally to technologies to implement rank multiplication. In February&nbsp;2010, Google answered the Company&#x2019;s complaint and asserted counterclaims against the Company seeking a declaration that the patent is invalid and not infringed, and claiming that the Company committed fraud, negligent misrepresentation and breach of contract based on the Company&#x2019;s activities in the JEDEC standard-setting organization. The counterclaim seeks unspecified compensatory damages. Accruals have not been recorded for loss contingencies related to Google&#x2019;s counterclaim because it is not probable that a loss has been incurred and the amount of any such loss cannot be reasonably estimated. In October&nbsp;2010, Google requested and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;912 patent by the USPTO. The reexamination proceedings are described below. In connection with the reexamination request, the Northern District Court granted the Company and Google&#x2019;s joint request to stay the &#x2018;912 patent infringement lawsuit against Google until the completion of the reexamination proceedings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inphi Litigation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In September&nbsp;2009, the Company filed a patent infringement lawsuit against Inphi Corporation (&#x201C;Inphi&#x201D;) in the U.S. District Court for the Central District of California (the &#x201C;Central District Court&#x201D;). The complaint, as amended, alleges that Inphi is contributorily infringing and actively inducing the infringement of U.S. patents owned by the Company, including the &#x2018;912 patent, U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;7,532,537 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;537 patent&#x201D;), which relates generally to memory modules with load isolation and memory domain translation capabilities, and U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;7,636,274 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;274 patent&#x201D;), which is related to the &#x2018;537 patent and relates generally to load isolation and memory domain translation technologies. The Company is seeking damages and injunctive relief based on Inphi&#x2019;s use of the Company&#x2019;s patented technology. Inphi denied infringement and claimed that the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patents are invalid. In April&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi requested but was later denied
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexaminations of the &#x2018;912, &#x2018;537 and &#x2018;274 patents by the USPTO. In June&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi submitted new requests and was later granted
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexaminations of the &#x2018;912, &#x2018;537 and &#x2018;274 patents by the USPTO. The reexamination proceedings are described below. In connection with the reexamination requests,&nbsp;Inphi filed a motion to stay the patent infringement lawsuit with the Central District Court, which was granted. The Central District Court has requested that the Company notify it within
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	week of any action taken by the USPTO in connection with the reexamination proceedings, at which time the Central District Court may decide to maintain or lift the stay.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	SanDisk, Smart Modular, Smart Worldwide, and Diablo Litigations
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In September&nbsp;2012, Smart Modular,&nbsp;Inc. (&#x201C;Smart Modular&#x201D;) filed a patent infringement lawsuit against the Company in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of California (the &#x201C;Eastern District Court&#x201D;). The complaint alleges that the Company willfully infringes and actively induces the infringement of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims of a U.S. patent newly issued to Smart Modular, U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;8,250,295 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;295 patent&#x201D;), and seeks damages and injunctive relief. Smart Modular also filed a motion for preliminary injunction and a memorandum in support of the motion on the same day of the complaint. The Company promptly filed a request for reexamination of the &#x2018;295 patent with the USPTO setting forth
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	different combinations of prior art that would render the six asserted claims of the &#x2018;295 patent unpatentable. The Company also filed an answer to Smart Modular&#x2019;s complaint with the Eastern District Court in October&nbsp;2012 to deny infringement of the &#x2018;295 patent, assert that the &#x2018;295 patent is invalid and unenforceable, and bring a set of counterclaims against Smart Modular. Smart Modular filed various motions on the pleadings on November&nbsp;1, 2012, which were opposed by the Company in its briefs filed in late November&nbsp;2012.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In December&nbsp;2012, the USPTO granted the Company&#x2019;s request for the reexamination of the &#x2018;295 patent, and issued an Office Action rejecting all of the six asserted claims over the six different combinations of prior art set forth by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	25
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage81"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	the Company in its request. The Company promptly moved to stay litigation pending result of reexamination. On February&nbsp;19, 2013, a few days after Smart Modular filed replies in support of its motions, the Eastern District Court issued a Minute Order, in which the court on its own motion took the preliminary injunction; the motion to dismiss and the motion to stay under submission without oral argument and vacated the hearing dates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On February&nbsp;7, 2013, Smart Modular filed a response to the Office Action in the reexamination of the &#x2018;295 patent. Thereafter, the Company and Smart Modular made various filings to address certain apparent defects contained in Smart Modular&#x2019;s response. On March&nbsp;13, 2013, the USPTO issued a Notice of Defective Paper, in which the USPTO found Smart Modular&#x2019;s responses, both the initial filing and a supplemental filing, to be improper, and both responses were expunged from the record. The USPTO gave Smart Modular
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	15
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;days to submit another response, which Smart Modular submitted on March&nbsp;26, 2013. The Company timely filed its comments on Smart Modular&#x2019;s corrected response on April&nbsp;25, 2013. The USPTO ultimately accepted Smart Modular&#x2019;s corrected response on July&nbsp;17, 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April&nbsp;29, 2014, the USPTO issued an Action Closing Prosecution (&#x201C;ACP&#x201D;), confirming some claims and rejecting others.&nbsp;&nbsp;Smart Modular filed a response to the ACP on May&nbsp;29, 2014, and Netlist filed comments related to Smart Modular&#x2019;s response on June&nbsp;30, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;On August 4, 2015, the USPTO issued a Right of Appeal Notice confirming all pending claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September 4, 2015, the Company appealed to the Patent Trial and Appeal Board (&#x201C;PTAB&#x201D;) at the USPTO. Thus, the reexamination of the &#x2018;295 patent remains pending and will continue in accordance with established procedures for reexamination proceedings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On May&nbsp;30, 2013, the Eastern District Court issued an order granting Netlist&#x2019;s motion to stay pending results of the reexamination of the &#x2018;295 patent and denied Smart Modular&#x2019;s motion for preliminary injunction.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On July&nbsp;1, 2013, Netlist filed a complaint against Smart Modular in the Santa Ana Division of the U.S. District Court for the Central District of California (&#x201C;Central District Court&#x201D;), seeking, among other things, relief under federal antitrust laws for Smart Modular&#x2019;s violation of Section&nbsp;2 of the Sherman Act, and damages and other equitable relief under California statutory and common law for Smart Modular&#x2019;s unfair competition, deceptive trade practices and fraud.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On August&nbsp;23, 2013, Netlist filed an amended complaint for patent infringement, antitrust violations and trade secret misappropriation against Smart Modular, Smart Storage Systems (&#x201C;Smart Storage&#x201D;), Smart Worldwide Holdings (&#x201C;Smart Worldwide&#x201D;) and Diablo Technologies (&#x201C;Diablo&#x201D;) in the Central District Court. Smart Storage was acquired by SanDisk Corporation (&#x201C;SanDisk&#x201D;) on August&nbsp;22, 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist&#x2019;s amended complaint alleges infringement of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	five
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Netlist patents by the defendants based on the manufacture and sale of the ULLtraDIMM memory module. Netlist&#x2019;s complaint also alleges antitrust violations by Smart Modular and Smart Worldwide, contending that Smart Modular procured the &#x2018;295 patent with blatant inequitable conduct at the USPTO, withheld the patent application leading to the patent from relevant JEDEC committees for more than
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	eight
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	years, sought to improperly enforce that patent against Netlist&#x2019;s JEDEC-compliant HyperCloud&#xAE; product by seeking a preliminary injunction against Netlist based on the patent, which was denied by the Eastern District Court, and made deceptive statements to the public about its lawsuit against Netlist. Netlist&#x2019;s complaint also alleges trade secret misappropriation and trademark infringement against Diablo, claiming that Diablo misused Netlist trade secrets to create the ULLtraDIMM product for Smart Storage (now SanDisk), and that Diablo used Netlist&#x2019;s HyperCloud&#xAE; technology to create competing products.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On the same day Netlist filed its amended complaint, Smart Modular and Diablo each filed a complaint in the San Francisco Division of the U.S. District Court Northern District of California (&#x201C;Northern District Court&#x201D;), seeking declaratory judgment of non-infringement and invalidity of the patents asserted in the Netlist&#x2019;s amended complaint. On September&nbsp;9, 2013, Netlist filed a Motion to Dismiss or Transfer these declaratory judgment complaints to the Central District Court. This motion was denied by the Northern District Court on October&nbsp;10, 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In the Central District Court, Smart Modular and Smart Worldwide filed motions on September&nbsp;13, 2013, to dismiss or sever various counts related to the &#x2018;295 patent. On September&nbsp;26, 2013, Diablo filed a motion to dismiss Netlist&#x2019;s claims for trade secret misappropriation, breach of contract, and unfair competition. On October&nbsp;29, 2013, Smart Modular and Diablo filed motions to dismiss or transfer the patent claims related to the ULLtraDIMM memory module. On November&nbsp;26, 2013, the Central District Court: (i)&nbsp;severed and transferred the claims related to the &#x2018;295 patent to the Eastern District Court, which were stayed by the Eastern District Court on March&nbsp;7, 2014, along with the other &#x2018;295 related claims pending results of the &#x2018;295 reexamination; (ii)&nbsp;severed and transferred to the Northern District
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	26
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage82"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Court the patent claims related to the ULLtraDIMM memory module; (iii)&nbsp;issued an order to show cause why the remaining claims should not also be transferred to the Northern District Court; and (iv)&nbsp;held in abeyance Diablo&#x2019;s pending motion to dismiss and motion for judgment on the pleadings. The parties filed briefs in response to the order to show cause, and then on December&nbsp;23, 2013, the Central District Court ordered the remaining claims to be transferred to the Northern District Court. All of the claims from the amended complaint filed on August&nbsp;23, 2013, in the Central District Court have now been transferred to either the Northern District Court or the Eastern District Court.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	As reported in its Current Report on Form&nbsp;8-K filed on December&nbsp;13, 2013, Netlist received a whistleblower letter postmarked from Canada (where Diablo is based) on November&nbsp;13, 2013, and obviously written by a current or former Diablo employee. The letter begins by bluntly stating that Diablo stole Netlist&#x2019;s architecture and design, and goes on to explain that Diablo used Netlist&#x2019;s HyperCloud
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	TM
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	product to create the ULLtraDIMM product, which it then used in demonstrations to major customers including IBM and Hewlett-Packard. The letter further states that Diablo&#x2019;s management conspired to hide this theft by instructing its employees not to speak to customers about the fact that Netlist&#x2019;s product was incorporated into ULLtraDIMM. The letter includes diagrams showing how Diablo implemented the theft of Netlist&#x2019;s trade secrets, as well as the names of former Diablo employees, customers and suppliers who can verify the theft. The Current Report on Form&nbsp;8-K included as an exhibit&nbsp;a partially redacted copy of the whistleblower letter. On December&nbsp;13, 2013, Diablo filed an ex parte application in the Northern District Court requesting that the Court issue an order to show cause why Netlist should not be sanctioned for attaching the redacted copy of the whistleblower letter to the Current Report on Form&nbsp;8-K. The Northern District Court heard the parties&#x2019; arguments on December&nbsp;16, 2013, and on January&nbsp;3, 2014, issued an order denying Diablo&#x2019;s application for sanctions, finding that Diablo had not established a basis for finding the information in the Current Report on Form&nbsp;8-K and its attachments &#x201C;confidential&#x201D; and therefore had not shown why it should be granted the relief sought.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On January&nbsp;21, 2014, Netlist filed a motion for leave to file&nbsp;a second amended answer and counterclaims in the Northern District Court to assert
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	additional patents, bringing the total to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	seven
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patents asserted against the ULLtraDIMM. Diablo did not oppose Netlist&#x2019;s motion, and the parties filed a joint stipulation and proposed order on February&nbsp;3, 2014, requesting an additional
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	months be added to the case schedule to account for the additional patents. On February&nbsp;5, 2014, the Northern District Court granted Netlist&#x2019;s motion to add the two patents and entered a new case schedule.&nbsp;&nbsp;On February&nbsp;12, 2014, the Northern District Court granted the parties&#x2019; joint stipulation dismissing Smart Modular without prejudice.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April&nbsp;7, 2014, the Northern District Court granted Netlist&#x2019;s motion for leave to file a Second Amended Complaint in the patent case.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On March&nbsp;21, 2014, Netlist filed a Second Amended Complaint against Diablo in the Northern District Court, Case No.&nbsp;4:13-CV-05962 (the &#x201C;trade secret case&#x201D;), alleging, among other things, that in stealing Netlist&#x2019;s proprietary HyperCloud&#xAE; and DxD and LRD technologies, Diablo breached its contracts with Netlist, committed trademark violations, and misappropriated Netlist&#x2019;s trade secrets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also on March&nbsp;21, 2014, Netlist served Diablo with its Amended Trade Secret Disclosure, detailing approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	60
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	trade secrets Netlist taught to Diablo in connection with the contracted and confidential work on the HyperCloud&#xAE; project.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April&nbsp;9, 2014, Diablo filed a motion to dismiss Netlist&#x2019;s Second Amended Trade Secret Complaint, as well as a motion for judgment on the pleadings.&nbsp;&nbsp;That motion was heard by the Northern District Court on May&nbsp;13, 2014, and on September&nbsp;4, 2014, denied the motion with respect to all grounds except
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, which Netlist did not contest.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On April&nbsp;1, 2014, the Northern District Court denied Diablo&#x2019;s motion to strike Netlist&#x2019;s infringement contentions, finding that Netlist&#x2019;s contentions did indeed satisfy the relevant requirements and, on April&nbsp;7, 2014, granted Netlist&#x2019;s motion to compel defendants to produce certain discovery materials related to the ULLtraDIMM.&nbsp;&nbsp;Diablo filed a motion for relief from these two rulings, which was denied on April&nbsp;8, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also on April&nbsp;7, 2014, the Northern District Court granted Netlist&#x2019;s motion for issuance of Letters Rogatory to the Canadian courts requesting that summons be issued for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	former Diablo employees living in Canada and named in the whistleblower letter to produce documents and to be deposed.&nbsp;&nbsp;These depositions occurred in late August 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On April&nbsp;8, 2014, the Northern District Court granted Netlist&#x2019;s motion to consolidate the patent related cases (Case Nos. 4:13-CV-05889-YGR and 4:13-CV-03901-YGR) and to coordinate discovery with the trade secret case (4:13-CV-05962-YGR), and denied Diablo&#x2019;s motion to further consolidate the patent and trade secret cases.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April&nbsp;15, 2014, the Northern District Court granted the parties&#x2019; joint stipulation dismissing Smart Worldwide without
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	27
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage83"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	prejudice.&nbsp;&nbsp;On April&nbsp;30, 2014, the Northern District Court denied Diablo&#x2019;s request that Netlist&#x2019;s Amended Trade Secret Disclosure and exhibits thereto be re-designated as &#x201C;Confidential&#x201D; from the current designation of &#x201C;Highly Confidential --Attorneys&#x2019; Eyes Only&#x201D;.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Between June&nbsp;18, 2014 and June&nbsp;24, 2014, SanDisk filed petitions in the USPTO requesting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Review (&#x201C;IPR&#x201D;) of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	the five Netlist patents asserted in the August&nbsp;23, 2013 amended complaint.&nbsp;&nbsp;Diablo similarly filed petitions requesting IPR of the two Netlist patents added in the second amended answer filed on January&nbsp;21, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed patent owner preliminary responses to all of the petitions associated with the seven asserted Netlist patents.&nbsp;&nbsp;The USPTO issued decisions on the petitions in December, 2014, denying the petitions in their entirety as to three patents (U.S. Patent Nos. 8,516,187; 8,301,833; 8,516,185), granting a partial institution on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patent (U.S. Patent No. 8,001,434), and instituting a review of all claims in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patents&nbsp;&nbsp;(U.S. Patent Nos. 7,881,150; 8,081,536; 8,359,501).&nbsp;&nbsp;Reviews will therefore proceed related to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Netlist patents (U.S. Patent Nos. 8,001,434; 7,881,150; 8,081,536; 8,359,501) in accordance with established procedures.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;On April 7, 2015, SanDisk filed additional petitions in the USPTO requesting IPR of the &#x2018;150 and &#x2018;536 patents that were already under review.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 8, 2015, the USPTO issued decisions on the additional petitions, instituting reviews of the &#x2018;150 and &#x2018;536 patents which will proceed in accordance with established procedures.&nbsp;&nbsp;On December 14, 2015, the PTAB issued decisions in the first wave of reviews of the &#x2018;434 and &#x2018;501 patents, finding that certain of the challenged claims in the &#x2018;434 and &#x2018;501 patents were valid, and that others were not.&nbsp;&nbsp;On the same day, the PTAB also issued decisions on the first wave of reviews of the &#x2018;150 and &#x2018;536 patents, finding all of the challenged claims invalid.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist and the petitioners will have an opportunity to appeal all of these decisions to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit (&#x201C;Federal Circuit&#x201D;) in accordance with established procedures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On August 23, 2014, Smart Modular also filed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	petitions in the USPTO requesting IPR of the five Netlist patents asserted in the August 23, 2013 amended complaint.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed patent owner preliminary responses to all of the Smart Modular petitions in December, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March 13, 2015, the USPTO issued decisions on the Smart Modular petitions, denying the petitions in their entirety as to the same
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patents that survived the petitions filed by SanDisk in June, 2014 (U.S. Patent Nos. 8,516,187; 8,301,833; 8,516,185), and instituted additional reviews of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	other patents already under review (U.S. Patent No. 8,001,434; 8,359,501) that will proceed in accordance
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	with established procedures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	SanDisk filed a motion on June&nbsp;24, 2014, to stay the Northern District patent cases pending completion of the IPRs (Diablo later joined this motion).&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed its opposition to the motion to stay on July&nbsp;10, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Northern District Court heard oral arguments on the motion to stay in early August&nbsp;2014, and issued an order on August&nbsp;21, 2014, denying the motion without prejudice.&nbsp;&nbsp;SanDisk renewed its motion to stay on January 20, 2015 and on April 9, 2015, the Court granted the motion for a stay pending resolution of the IPRs.&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	On October&nbsp;6, 2014, Netlist filed a Motion for Preliminary Injunction in the Northern District Court trade secret suit, asking that Diablo and its partner SanDisk be immediately enjoined from any further manufacture or sale of the ULLtraDIMM module.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Court granted in part Netlist&#x2019;s motion on January 6, 2015, and entered a preliminary injunction halting the manufacture, use, sale, or distribution of the Diablo Rush and Bolt chips and any ULLtraDIMM module containing those chips, and advanced the trial date to March 9, 2015 on the trade secret misappropriation, breach of contract, and other related claims (4:13-CV-05962-YGR).&nbsp;&nbsp;SanDisk and Diablo filed motions with the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit appealing the January 6, 2015, preliminary injunction and asking for expedited briefing and a stay of the preliminary injunction during the pendency of the appeals.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Federal Circuit denied both requests for expedited briefing, denied Diablo&#x2019;s request for a stay, but granted SanDisk&#x2019;s narrower request for a stay of the preliminary injunction as to SanDisk&#x2019;s existing inventory of enjoined products.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The trial commenced on schedule and continued
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	weeks
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, with closing arguments on March 23, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;On March 25, 2015, the jury came back with a verdict finding for the defendant on the breach of contract, misappropriation of trade secret and inventorship counts, while finding for Netlist on the trademark and false advertising counts. After the verdict, the court ordered briefing to determine the effect of the jury verdict on the preliminary injunction entered on January 6, 2015, and following oral argument on April 24, 2015, issued an order dissolving the preliminary injunction.&nbsp;&nbsp;The court further issued Findings of Fact and Conclusions of Law on Netlist&#x2019;s unfair competition claims granting no relief under the statute based on the jury&#x2019;s verdict.&nbsp;&nbsp;The parties briefed their post-trial
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	28
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	motions in May and June of 2015, including Netlist&#x2019;s motion for Judgment as a Matter of Law (&#x201C;JMOL&#x201D;) to reverse the jury&#x2019;s verdict as to breach of contract and for a new trial on misappropriation of trade secrets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Oral arguments on the post-trial motions were heard by the court on July 8, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September 1, 2015, the Court denied motions from both parties for JMOL, Netlist&#x2019;s motion for a new trial, and Diablo&#x2019;s motion for attorney&#x2019;s fees, but granted Diablo&#x2019;s motion to recover on the preliminary
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	injunction a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	$900,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	bond posted
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	early in the litigation and its bill of costs. This expense is included in other expense, net in the accompanying consolidated statements of operation for the year ended January 2, 2016. On September 29, 2015, Netlist filed a Notice of Appeal to the Federal Circuit and on December 8, 2015, filed an Opening Brief.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist&#x2019;s appeal will continue in accordance with established procedures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x2018;386 Patent Reexamination
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	As noted above, in May&nbsp;2010, Google requested and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;386 patent by the USPTO. In October&nbsp;2010, Smart Modular requested and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;386 patent. The reexaminations requested by Google and Smart Modular were merged by the USPTO into a single proceeding. In April&nbsp;2011, a Non-Final Action was issued by the USPTO, rejecting all claims in the patent. In July&nbsp;2011, the Company responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims in view of cited references. Both Google and Smart Modular filed their comments to the Company&#x2019;s response in October&nbsp;2011. In October&nbsp;2012, the USPTO issued an ACP rejecting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	60
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	. The Company filed a response to the ACP on December&nbsp;3, 2012. On June&nbsp;21, 2013, the USPTO issued a Right of Appeal Notice (&#x201C;RAN&#x201D;) in which the examiner maintained his rejection of the claims. Netlist filed a notice of appeal on July&nbsp;19, 2013. Google filed a notice of cross-appeal on August&nbsp;2, 2013, and a cross-appeal brief on October&nbsp;1, 2013. The Company filed an appeal brief and an amendment canceling some of the remaining claims on October&nbsp;2, 2013 to further focus the issues on appeal. On February&nbsp;24, 2014, the examiner entered the amendment canceling claims, withdrew the rejections related to those claims, but otherwise maintained the positions previously set forth in the RAN.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September&nbsp;24, 2014, the USPTO set a hearing date of November&nbsp;19, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;After the hearing, on February 25, 2015, the PTAB issued a decision affirming the examiner&#x2019;s rejections of the pending claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company requested rehearing of the PTAB&#x2019;s decision on March 25, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;On August 27, 2015, the PTAB denied the Company&#x2019;s request for rehearing.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist appealed to the Federal Circuit on October 26, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The appeal was dismissed on January 28, 2016 by Netlist.&nbsp;&nbsp;Thus, while the reexamination of the &#x2018;386 patent remains pending, it will terminate in accordance with established procedures for merged reexamination proceedings in due course with the cancellation of the original claims.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x2018;912 Patent Reexamination
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	As noted above, in April&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi requested but was later denied an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;912 patent by the USPTO. In June&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi submitted a new request and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;912 patent by the USPTO. In September&nbsp;2010, the USPTO
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	confirmed the patentability of all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	fifty-one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims of the &#x2018;912 patent. In October&nbsp;2010, Google and Smart Modular each filed and were later granted requests for reexamination of the &#x2018;912 patent. In February&nbsp;2011, the USPTO merged the Inphi, Google and Smart Modular &#x2018;912 reexaminations into a single proceeding. In an April&nbsp;2011 Non-Final Action in the merged reexamination proceeding, the USPTO rejected claims 1-20 and 22-51 and confirmed the patentability of claim 21 of the &#x2018;912 patent. In July&nbsp;2011, the Company responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Inphi, Google, and Smart Modular filed their comments on the Company&#x2019;s response in August&nbsp;2011. In October&nbsp;2011, the USPTO mailed a second Non-Final Action confirming the patentability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	twenty
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims of the &#x2018;912 patent, including claims that were added in the reexamination process. In January&nbsp;2012, the Company responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Google,&nbsp;Inphi and Smart Modular filed their comments to the Company&#x2019;s response in February&nbsp;2012. The USPTO determined that Smart Modular&#x2019;s comments were defective, and issued a notice to Smart Modular to rectify and resubmit its comments. Smart Modular filed corrected comments and a petition for the USPTO to withdraw the notice in March&nbsp;2012. The USPTO issued a non-final Office Action on November&nbsp;13, 2012 maintaining the patentability of many key claims while rejecting some claims that were previously determined to be patentable. The Company filed a response to the Office Action on January&nbsp;14, 2013. The requesters filed their comments on February&nbsp;13, 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;21, 2014, the USPTO issued an ACP, confirming the patentability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	92
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims and maintaining the rejection of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	11
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	other claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;On June&nbsp;18, 2014, the USPTO issued a RAN, maintaining the substantive positions taken by the examiner in the ACP.&nbsp;&nbsp;Smart Modular,&nbsp;Inphi and Google
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	filed notices of appeal on July&nbsp;16,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	29
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

	&nbsp;

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>

</DIV>

<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	July&nbsp;18 and July&nbsp;18, 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed a notice of cross-appeal on July&nbsp;30, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Smart Modular,&nbsp;Inphi and Google filed their respective appeal briefs on September&nbsp;16, September&nbsp;30 and September&nbsp;30, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed its cross-appeal brief on September&nbsp;30, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;On January 14, 2015, the examiner maintained his positions previously set forth in the RAN.&nbsp;&nbsp;The parties filed respective rebuttal briefs in February 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September 29, 2015, the PTAB set a hearing date for November 24, 2015 on the parties&#x2019; appeals.&nbsp;&nbsp;The hearing was conducted on November 24, 2015, and the parties are awaiting the USPTO&#x2019;s decision.&nbsp;&nbsp;Thus, the reexamination of the &#x2018;912 patent remains pending and will continue in accordance with established procedures for merged reexamination proceedings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x2018;627 Patent Reexamination
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	In September&nbsp;2011, Smart Modular filed a request for reexamination of U.S. Patent No.&nbsp;7,864,627 (&#x201C;the &#x2018;627 patent&#x201D;) issued to the Company on January&nbsp;4, 2011. The &#x2018;627 patent is related to the &#x2018;912&nbsp;patent. In November&nbsp;2011, the USPTO granted Smart Modular&#x2019;s request for reexamination of the &#x2018;627 patent and concurrently issued a Non-Final Action confirming the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patentability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	three
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims. In February&nbsp;2012, the Company responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Smart Modular filed its comments to the Company&#x2019;s response in March&nbsp;2012. The USPTO determined that Smart Modular&#x2019;s comments were defective and issued a notice in April&nbsp;2012 to Smart Modular to rectify and resubmit its comments. Smart Modular filed corrected comments and a petition for the USPTO to withdraw the notice in April&nbsp;2012. The USPTO posted an Office Action on December&nbsp;19, 2012, confirming
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claim
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	and rejecting the rest of the claims in the &#x2018;627 patent. The Company filed a response to the Office Action on March&nbsp;19, 2013. Smart Modular filed its comments on the Office Action on April&nbsp;24, 2013. The USPTO issued another Non-Final Office Action on September&nbsp;26, 2013, withdrawing certain rejections while adopting new rejections for certain of the pending claims. The Company responded to the Non-Final Office Action on November&nbsp;26, 2013, by amending some of the claims and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. On March&nbsp;27, 2014, the USPTO issued an ACP, maintaining the claim rejections.&nbsp;&nbsp;On June&nbsp;27, 2014, the USPTO issued a RAN, maintaining the substantive positions taken by the examiner in the ACP.&nbsp;&nbsp;Netlist filed a notice of appeal on July&nbsp;28, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 14, 2014, the Company filed its appeal brief and, on November 13, 2014, Smart Modular filed its respondent&#x2019;s brief. On April 27, 2015, the USPTO issued an Examiner&#x2019;s Answer to Appeal Brief in which the examiner continued to maintain the substantive positions taken previously.&nbsp;&nbsp;On May 27, 2015, the Company filed a Patent Owner Rebuttal Brief in response to the Examiner&#x2019;s Answer. On October 9, 2015, the PTAB set a hearing date for December 11, 2015 on the Company&#x2019;s appeal.&nbsp;&nbsp;The hearing was conducted on November 24, 2015, and the parties are awaiting the USPTO&#x2019;s decision.&nbsp;&nbsp;Thus, the reexamination of the &#x2018;627 patent remains pending and will continue in accordance with established
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination procedures.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x2018;537 Patent Reexamination
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	As noted above, in April&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi requested and was later denied an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;537 patent by the USPTO. In June&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi submitted a new request and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;537 patent by the USPTO. In September&nbsp;2010, the USPTO issued a Non-Final Action confirming the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patentability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims. In October&nbsp;2010, the Company responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Inphi filed its comments on the Company&#x2019;s response in January&nbsp;2011. In June&nbsp;2011, the USPTO issued an ACP, which reconfirmed the patentability of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims. In August&nbsp;2010, the Company responded by amending some of the claims and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Inphi filed its comments to the Company&#x2019;s response in September&nbsp;2011. The USPTO issued a Right of Appeal Notice in February&nbsp;2012, in which the claim rejections were withdrawn, thus confirming the patentability of all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	sixty
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	(60)&nbsp;claims in view of all the previously submitted comments by both Inphi and the Company. Inphi filed a notice of appeal in March&nbsp;2012 followed by an appeal brief in May&nbsp;2012. In response, the USPTO issued a Notice of Defective Appeal Brief. Inphi filed a corrective appeal brief in late May&nbsp;2012, and the Company filed its reply brief to the corrected Inphi appeal brief in early July&nbsp;2012. The examiner responded to Inphi&#x2019;s corrected appeal brief as well as the Company&#x2019;s reply brief by Examiner&#x2019;s Answer on April&nbsp;16, 2013, in which he maintained his position confirming all sixty (60)&nbsp;claims. Inphi filed a rebuttal brief on May&nbsp;16, 2013. Netlist filed a request for oral hearing on June&nbsp;14, 2013. The Company and the examiner jointly defended the &#x2018;537 patent in a hearing on November&nbsp;20, 2013 before the PTAB. On January&nbsp;16, 2014, the PTAB issued a decision upholding the validity of all
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	60
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims, dismissing every single validity challenge raised by Inphi and affirming the examiner&#x2019;s decision to allow the claims
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	. On August&nbsp;13, 2014, the PTAB denied Inphi&#x2019;s request for rehearing and made its decision final for judicial review to the Federal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
</FONT>
</P>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:24PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	F-
</FONT>

<HR ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE='BACKGROUND-COLOR:#000000; BORDER-WIDTH:0; COLOR:#000000; HEIGHT:2PT; LINEHEIGHT:0; WIDTH:100%;'>

<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage86"></A>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 18PT;COLOR:#0563C1;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<A HREF="#NLST-20160102X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#0563C1;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
</DIV>
</DIV>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN-LEFT:10.2941176470588%;MARGIN-RIGHT:10.2941176470588%;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Circuit.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 15, 2014, Inphi filed a Notice of Appeal to the Federal Circuit.&nbsp;&nbsp;On February 3, 2015, Inphi filed an appellant&#x2019;s brief in its appeal to the Federal Circuit.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company filed its appellee&#x2019;s brief on May 18, 2015, and Inphi filed a reply brief on June 4, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 9, 2015, the Federal Circuit conducted a hearing on Inphi&#x2019;s appeal.&nbsp;&nbsp;On November 13, 2015, a panel of the Federal Circuit unanimously ruled in favor of Netlist in a precedential decision.&nbsp;&nbsp;Inphi petitioned for panel rehearing and en banc rehearing on December 14, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Both petitions were denied on January 22, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;Inphi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	has
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	90
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	days to petition
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	the U.S. Supreme Court for certiorari.&nbsp;&nbsp;Thus, the reexamination of the &#x2018;537 patent remains pending and will continue in accordance with established procedures for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination and judicial appeals therefrom.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x2018;274 Patent Reexamination
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	As noted above, in April&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi requested and was later denied an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;274 patent by the USPTO. In June&nbsp;2010,&nbsp;Inphi submitted a new request and was later granted an
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination of the &#x2018;274 patent by the USPTO. In September&nbsp;2011, the USPTO issued a Non-Final Action, confirming the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	patentability of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	six
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	claims. The Company has responded by amending or canceling some of the claims, adding new claims, and making arguments as to the validity of the rejected claims. Inphi filed its comments on the Company&#x2019;s response in November&nbsp;2011. The USPTO issued an ACP in March&nbsp;2012, which confirmed the patentability of one hundred and four
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	(104)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;claims in view of all the previously submitted comments by both Inphi and the Company. The USPTO subsequently issued a RAN in June&nbsp;2012. This RAN triggered Inphi&#x2019;s right as the losing party to file&nbsp;a notice of appeal and corresponding appeal brief, which Inphi filed when due. The Company responded to Inphi&#x2019;s appeal brief by filing a reply brief in October&nbsp;2012. The examiner responded to Inphi&#x2019;s appeal brief and the reply brief by Examiner&#x2019;s Answer on April&nbsp;16, 2013, in which he maintained his position confirming the one hundred and four (104)&nbsp;claims. Inphi filed a rebuttal brief on May&nbsp;16, 2013. Netlist filed a request for oral hearing on June&nbsp;14, 2013. The Company and the USPTO examiner jointly defended the &#x2018;274 patent in a hearing on November&nbsp;20, 2013 before the PTAB, in accordance with established procedures for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination. On January&nbsp;16, 2014, the PTAB issued a decision affirming the examiner in part, but reversing the examiner on new grounds and rejecting the one hundred and four (104)&nbsp;claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March&nbsp;28, 2014, Netlist filed a Patent Owner&#x2019;s Response Requesting to Reopen Prosecution along with certain claim amendments and arguments.&nbsp;&nbsp;On June&nbsp;26, 2014, the PTAB issued a decision granting-in-part Inphi&#x2019;s request to modify the January&nbsp;16, 2014, decision as to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	two
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	of the rejected claims. On June 15, 2015, the USPTO issued an Examiner&#x2019;s Determination, rejecting the amended claims.&nbsp;&nbsp;On July
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	8, 2015, the USPTO vacated sua sponte the June 15 Examiner&#x2019;s Determination.&nbsp;&nbsp;On September 11, 2015, the examiner issued a new Examiner&#x2019;s Determination which rejected the amended claims based on multiple grounds.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 13, 2015, the Company filed a response to the Examiner&#x2019;s Determination.&nbsp;&nbsp;The reexamination of the &#x2018;274 patent remains pending and will continue in accordance with established procedures for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Inter Partes
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Reexamination.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Other Contingent Obligations
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 9PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	During its normal course of business, the Company has made certain indemnities, commitments and guarantees pursuant to which it may be required to make payments in relation to certain transactions. These include: (i)&nbsp;intellectual property indemnities to the Company&#x2019;s customers and licensees in connection with the use, sales and/or license of Company products; (ii)&nbsp;indemnities to vendors and service providers pertaining to claims based on the Company&#x2019;s negligence or willful misconduct; (iii)&nbsp;indemnities involving the accuracy of representations and warranties in certain contracts; (iv)&nbsp;indemnities to directors and officers of the Company to the maximum extent permitted under the laws of the State of Delaware; (v) indemnities to Fortress, SVIC, and SVB pertaining to all obligations, demands, claims, and liabilities claimed or asserted by any other party in connection with transactions contemplated by the loan documents; and (vi)&nbsp;certain real estate leases, under which the Company may be required to indemnify property owners for environmental and other liabilities, and other claims arising from the Company&#x2019;s use of the applicable premises. The duration of these indemnities, commitments and guarantees varies and, in certain cases, may be indefinite. The majority of these indemnities, commitments and guarantees do not provide for any limitation of the maximum potential for future payments the Company could be obligated to make. Historically, the Company has not been obligated to make significant payments for these obligations, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	no
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	liabilities have been recorded for these indemnities, commitments and guarantees in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

	of shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock. In the 2014 Offering, the Company issued and sold to

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	Underwriter

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The Company is incorporated in the state of Delaware, and as such, is subject to various state laws which may restrict the payment of dividends or purchase of treasury shares.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Stock-Based Compensation
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 0PT 0PT 54PT;TEXT-INDENT: -18PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The Company has stock-based compensation awards outstanding pursuant to the Amended and Restated 2000 Equity Incentive Plan (the &#x201C;2000 Plan&#x201D;) and the Amended and Restated 2006 Equity Incentive Plan (the &#x201C;2006 Plan&#x201D;), under which a variety of option and direct stock-based awards may be granted to employees and nonemployees of the Company. Further grants under the 2000 Plan were suspended upon the adoption of the 2006 Plan. In addition to awards made pursuant to the 2006 Plan, the Company periodically issues inducement grants outside the 2006 Plan to certain new hires.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">

	Subject to certain adjustments, as of January 2, 2016, the Company was authorized to issue a maximum of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	10,205,566
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	shares of common stock pursuant to awards under the 2006 Plan. Pursuant to the terms of the 2006 Plan, the maximum number of shares of common stock subject to the plan automatically increased on the first day of each subsequent calendar year through January 1, 2016, by the lesser of (i)&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	5.0%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	of the number of shares of common stock that are issued and outstanding as of the first day of the calendar year, and (ii)&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	1,200,000
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	shares of common stock, subject to adjustment for certain corporate actions. At January 2, 2016, the Company had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	1,179,375
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	shares available for issuance under the 2006 Plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;Options granted under the 2000 Plan and the 2006 Plan equity incentive plans primarily vest at a rate of at least
</FONT>

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>

	10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;years from the date of grant.

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>

	6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, net of estimated forfeitures. The weighted-average period over which the unearned stock-based compensation is expected to be recognized is approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	2.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	years. If there are any modifications or cancellations of the underlying unvested awards, the Company may be required to accelerate, increase or cancel any remaining unearned stock-based compensation expense or calculate and record additional expense.&nbsp;&nbsp;Future stock-based compensation expense and unearned stock-based compensation will increase to the extent that the Company grants additional common stock options or other stock-based awards.
</FONT>

See Note 5 for further information. The Fortress Warrant and amended Drawbridge Warrant were valued

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	The Company sponsors a 401(k) defined contribution plan. Employees are eligible to participate in this plan provided they are employed full-time and have reached
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	21
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	&nbsp;years of age. Participants may make pre-tax contributions to the plan subject to a statutorily prescribed annual limit. Each participant is fully vested in his or her contributions and investment earnings. The Company may make matching contributions on the contributions of a participant on a discretionary basis. In fiscal 2012, the Company adopted a limited matching contribution policy and made approximately
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	$
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	.

	&nbsp;

</FONT>

	$0.0
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	in contributions to participants in this plan in the year

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	s

	ended

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 10PT;">

	The Company operates in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	one
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	reportable segment: the design and manufacture of high-performance memory subsystems for the server, high-performance computing and communications markets. The Company evaluates financial performance on a company-wide basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 8PT;">

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">

	the Company&#x2019;s net
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	product

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	5

</FONT>

	4

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;">
	, respectively. All of the Company&#x2019;s net sales to date have been denominated in U.S. dollars.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:26PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;TEXT-TRANSFORM:UPPERCASE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	1.
</FONT>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:4PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;TEXT-TRANSFORM:UPPERCASE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Definitions
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;As used in this Agreement, the following terms have the following meanings:
</FONT>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;TEXT-INDENT:36PT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:72PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:22PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	(a)
</FONT>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:4PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x201C;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Accounts Collateral
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x201D; means Borrower&#x2019;s present and future &#x201C;accounts&#x201D; (as defined in the UCC), including accounts arising from testing and other services performed, or goods created, by Borrower using patents, copyrights or other intellectual property of Borrower, but not including proceeds of any sale of any Creditor Priority Collateral.
</FONT>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:72PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:72PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:22PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	(b)
</FONT>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="TEXT-INDENT:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT; PADDING-RIGHT:4PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x201C;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;TEXT-DECORATION:UNDERLINE;">
	Bank Priority Collateral
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&#x201D; means any and all properties, rights and assets of Borrower described on Exhibit B, but excluding the Creditor Priority Collateral.
</FONT>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:72PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;TEXT-JUSTIFY:INTER-IDEOGRAPH;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN,TIMES,SERIF;FONT-SIZE: 12PT;">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	&nbsp;

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY:INLINE;COLOR:#000000;FONT-SIZE:12PT;">
	(a)
